{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638338"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:52:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:52:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17700"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17700"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72117"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10414"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17700"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57587"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10420"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24325"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24362"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72117"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe accommodation reflex allows clear vision of objects at varying distances from the eye.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the changes that occur in the eye when focusing on a near object?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ciliary muscle contraction with increased lens convexity","Ciliary muscle relaxation with pupillary constriction","Pupillary dilation with lens flattening","Ciliary muscle relaxation with lens flattening","Pupillary constriction with lens flattening"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen focusing on near objects, \u003Cstrong\u003Eciliary muscle contraction with increased lens convexity\u003C/strong\u003E occurs as part of the accommodation reflex. The ciliary muscles contract under parasympathetic stimulation, releasing tension on the suspensory ligaments. This allows the elastic lens to assume a more convex shape, increasing its refractive power.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiliary muscle relaxation with lens flattening\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs when focusing on distant objects, not near objects.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPupillary dilation with lens flattening\u003C/strong\u003E - The pupil constricts rather than dilates for near vision, and the lens becomes more convex rather than flattening.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPupillary constriction with lens flattening\u003C/strong\u003E - While pupillary constriction is correct for near vision, the lens becomes more convex rather than flattening.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiliary muscle relaxation with pupillary constriction\u003C/strong\u003E - The ciliary muscle contracts rather than relaxes during accommodation for near vision.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe complete near response triad consists of lens accommodation (increased convexity), pupillary constriction (miosis), and convergence of the eyes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The accommodation reflex involves coordinated changes in lens shape, pupil size, and eye convergence to focus on near objects.","Parasympathetic stimulation causes contraction of the ciliary muscles, which allows the lens to become more convex.","The near response triad consists of increased lens convexity, pupillary constriction, and convergence of the eyes."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57587"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17700"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57587"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:44:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:45:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10414"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72117"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://ap